WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.760
Hi everyone, I'm excited to be starting off the session. Today I'm going to be talking less about

00:00:05.760 --> 00:00:10.720
some shiny new tool that you can use, but more about rethinking what we do with these tools

00:00:10.720 --> 00:00:16.879
and how we use them. In particular, in the context of feedback. Feedback's valuable,

00:00:16.879 --> 00:00:22.160
it's how we know how to make changes. I'm sure we've all seen feedback forms come up,

00:00:22.160 --> 00:00:26.719
for example on websites when you're booking a flight, that ask you a bunch of questions.

00:00:26.799 --> 00:00:31.360
And this can be an annoying experience. You just want to click away the pop-up, make it go away,

00:00:32.720 --> 00:00:36.480
and you don't really want to fill it out, you don't really want to provide good information

00:00:36.480 --> 00:00:43.279
a lot of the time. So a big question is how do we get good feedback? Not just in the case of

00:00:43.279 --> 00:00:49.279
websites or online experiences, but also once we start to think about organizations. Because

00:00:49.279 --> 00:00:54.720
feedback's the way we know what is going on in my team and organization, or more often than not,

00:00:54.720 --> 00:01:00.720
what's going wrong and how can I fix it? So we have to think through what is the process of

00:01:00.720 --> 00:01:07.440
getting feedback and what does it feel like for the people providing the feedback. In organizations,

00:01:07.440 --> 00:01:11.360
sometimes you're doing employee engagement surveys, sometimes you're getting information

00:01:11.360 --> 00:01:16.400
in other ways, but a lot of times it can still just feel like kind of like putting a card in

00:01:16.400 --> 00:01:21.519
a suggestion box. You put it in and you just don't know what's going to happen with it,

00:01:21.519 --> 00:01:24.559
I'm maybe not sure who's going to read it, how they're going to interpret it,

00:01:24.559 --> 00:01:28.400
is something ever going to come of that feedback, or is it just going to sit there forever?

00:01:29.919 --> 00:01:36.959
Even once we've switched to digital surveys, a lot of these same feelings still persist,

00:01:36.959 --> 00:01:42.639
it still affects how we think about things. So what I want to talk about today is some of the

00:01:42.639 --> 00:01:47.599
challenges in getting good information from employees or other people in an organization.

00:01:48.559 --> 00:01:53.120
So when you have an employee feedback survey, there's a lot of different pain points or

00:01:53.120 --> 00:01:59.040
challenges that can occur and some underlying ethical questions relating to them. The first

00:01:59.040 --> 00:02:04.000
one is time and motivation. People are busy, people have different things in their job,

00:02:04.000 --> 00:02:07.279
and a lot of times people aren't going to want to fill out a feedback survey.

00:02:08.559 --> 00:02:13.360
You may have like a million emails in your inbox and just another one is, oh, reminder,

00:02:13.360 --> 00:02:19.119
please fill out the survey by Friday. It can be frustrating, so you either end up with people

00:02:19.119 --> 00:02:23.839
not doing the feedback survey, or you get people just filling it out as quickly as possible,

00:02:23.839 --> 00:02:30.160
sometimes not putting in good or meaningful responses. In both cases, you're bad. Forcing

00:02:30.160 --> 00:02:34.559
someone to like answer a survey if they don't provide good information isn't really helping

00:02:34.559 --> 00:02:42.160
anyone at all. The second point of challenge is privacy or trust. Who's going to be receiving

00:02:42.160 --> 00:02:47.360
the feedback and are they going to receive it in a positive light? What's kind of the potential

00:02:47.360 --> 00:02:52.479
impact and what's the potential harm? This is important, especially when you're asking people

00:02:52.479 --> 00:02:57.440
about their job. No one in a feedback survey is really going to say, oh, I'm doing a poor job,

00:02:58.080 --> 00:03:03.839
or they may be very hesitant to say something like, oh, I think this is going wrong, when negative

00:03:03.839 --> 00:03:09.440
feedback about another department, about a project could affect their co-workers and could affect

00:03:10.320 --> 00:03:15.839
their friends in a negative light. So you have to really think about how can I make people feel safe

00:03:16.399 --> 00:03:23.279
and feel validated to give honest responses? Finally, you have to think about impact and the

00:03:23.279 --> 00:03:27.839
way it can affect things. When you're providing information, you don't necessarily know how it's

00:03:27.839 --> 00:03:34.720
going to be used. If I say something that even if I think it's a positive light, together with other

00:03:34.720 --> 00:03:39.600
information, other context, other motives from decision makers, it could have an unexpected

00:03:39.600 --> 00:03:45.039
effect. So when I'm filling out feedback, I may be hesitant or I may be thinking about like what can

00:03:45.039 --> 00:03:51.679
go wrong? Do I trust this process? All of these pain points make collecting data hard. How do I

00:03:51.679 --> 00:03:58.240
get an honest, high quality view of what's going on in an organization? And sometimes organizations

00:03:58.240 --> 00:04:02.720
can become really desperate when they're dealing with this. Either they're sending a million emails

00:04:02.720 --> 00:04:08.880
and reminders constantly bugging people, or in the case of one organization I worked with, they

00:04:08.880 --> 00:04:13.919
started to force people's responses where it would literally lock employees out of the system if they

00:04:13.919 --> 00:04:18.959
hadn't completed the feedback surveys on time and they would have to go through and do it. And that's

00:04:18.959 --> 00:04:23.760
a good way to get 100% response rate, but it's not necessarily a good way to really know what's

00:04:23.760 --> 00:04:29.760
going on in your organization. Is there a more organic way we can do this? And that's why today

00:04:29.760 --> 00:04:35.040
I'm going to be thinking through the impacts of these bad incentives on surveys. They can hurt

00:04:35.040 --> 00:04:40.640
data quality, they can make it hard to take these responses and actually change organizations,

00:04:40.640 --> 00:04:47.279
and what can we do about it? How can we get a better experience? And can we use some of these

00:04:47.279 --> 00:04:54.000
tools like Shiny, Quarto, or even Markdown to start to change the way we design surveys and

00:04:54.000 --> 00:04:59.200
deliver results to address these pain points? So that's our goal for today, to kind of think through

00:04:59.200 --> 00:05:04.880
the process. So to talk through what I did, I want to give you a little bit more context about my own

00:05:04.880 --> 00:05:10.720
work. I'm an academic, I'm at Grinnell, and I was working on this project with several amazing

00:05:10.720 --> 00:05:16.320
collaborators at Northwestern. And we study networks, how people are connected to others

00:05:16.320 --> 00:05:21.040
within a team or an organization. And we were looking at this in several companies in the

00:05:21.040 --> 00:05:26.799
context of COVID, trying to understand what is going on, how are people seeking advice, providing

00:05:26.799 --> 00:05:32.480
leadership and connecting in these challenging times. And the way we do this is by asking

00:05:32.480 --> 00:05:38.160
questions that build these sort of network models of who do people go to for advice, where are these

00:05:38.160 --> 00:05:44.399
silos in the department, where the whole network is bigger than the sum of its parts. So this is

00:05:44.399 --> 00:05:50.079
really reliant on surveys. You have to ask people about connections like advice, leadership, trust.

00:05:50.079 --> 00:05:54.480
These are all things that only exist in people's heads. They're not something that you can quantify

00:05:54.480 --> 00:06:00.880
with some like digital trace data. So as we started to conduct research, we were working

00:06:00.880 --> 00:06:05.200
with different companies, and we would work with the management and leadership in the company.

00:06:06.399 --> 00:06:10.720
So what you typically do in this network survey environment is you survey all the employees in

00:06:10.720 --> 00:06:16.000
the department, you combine all the responses, so all the employees are the individual nodes in that

00:06:16.000 --> 00:06:21.920
network, and you look at the big picture, and you try to give the management some type of top-level

00:06:21.920 --> 00:06:28.160
insight, takeaways, and rely on them to make changes. But this is all dependent on getting

00:06:28.160 --> 00:06:34.640
good data. We only act on what we can see, and if you ask people a question like who's making tasks

00:06:34.640 --> 00:06:40.079
difficult to complete, who do you enjoy working with, what are the challenges on your team,

00:06:40.079 --> 00:06:44.559
you may not get accurate answers when you're trying to ask employees that when it's coming

00:06:44.559 --> 00:06:51.519
from their boss. And that's the problem is this framing, it's focused on me as the academic or

00:06:51.519 --> 00:06:56.480
the management or leadership of an organization of taking action. We gather data, we put the data

00:06:56.480 --> 00:07:03.200
together, we get a good report, and we see what's going on. That kind of framing though isn't putting

00:07:03.200 --> 00:07:07.519
the participants that are actually taking time to fill out the survey first. We're not thinking

00:07:07.519 --> 00:07:14.160
about their own user experiences, and that's kind of the big challenge. So how do we rethink this?

00:07:14.799 --> 00:07:21.040
In the model before, if we wanted to improve the organization, fix problems, it's all about sort of

00:07:21.040 --> 00:07:27.519
top-down change. We have this network map, we give some key insights to management, and management or

00:07:27.519 --> 00:07:31.839
leadership is going to change something, and they're going to fix something about the organization.

00:07:31.839 --> 00:07:37.519
They're going to have one cohesive strategy. We started to ask what's the alternative?

00:07:38.320 --> 00:07:43.440
What if instead of trying to just help management, we tried to give value directly to the participants

00:07:43.440 --> 00:07:48.559
in the survey? So instead of the management knowing everything, people being concerned about

00:07:48.559 --> 00:07:54.640
their privacy and trust, will they use the information well? What if we give every individual

00:07:54.640 --> 00:07:59.760
their own tiny piece of the puzzle? We give them information about their own local network based

00:07:59.760 --> 00:08:04.640
off of the responses they provide, and we empower all of them to make changes. Changes are going to

00:08:04.640 --> 00:08:10.799
come from the bottom up, and hopefully help out everyone in the company. So that's what we started

00:08:10.799 --> 00:08:16.480
to do with some of these companies. So we started building this tool called the Personalized Network

00:08:16.480 --> 00:08:23.359
Report, and the big picture idea that we had for this is, can we take your survey responses, and can

00:08:23.359 --> 00:08:29.279
we give you back value based off of them? So instead of taking your survey responses, fill this out,

00:08:29.279 --> 00:08:33.520
you'll never directly hear from us again after it's done, and we're going to give some aggregate

00:08:33.520 --> 00:08:37.599
information to your boss that you're going to hope does something well with it, and hope your

00:08:37.599 --> 00:08:43.520
responses aren't harmful to others. Can we take your responses, and can we deliver value to you?

00:08:44.479 --> 00:08:51.280
So in some sense, we're just circling back the data that they provide to them, but in some other

00:08:51.280 --> 00:08:56.159
senses, we're giving them context on how to interpret it, insights on how to look at a network,

00:08:56.159 --> 00:09:01.280
what does it mean, how do I compare to others on average, and helping them think through the process.

00:09:01.919 --> 00:09:08.320
And that's the idea, to help every individual make changes, rather than trying to just benefit

00:09:08.320 --> 00:09:14.000
management and just give information to management. Completely rethinking power balance.

00:09:15.679 --> 00:09:21.119
So what did this look like? When we were running it with organizations, it was moving from something

00:09:21.119 --> 00:09:25.840
that felt like running a survey, to something more like a professional development workshop.

00:09:26.400 --> 00:09:30.799
We'd have participants fill out this questionnaire, they would describe their networks, they would get

00:09:30.799 --> 00:09:35.359
this personalized feedback report, and then we would go into the companies and we would do a

00:09:35.359 --> 00:09:40.080
workshop with them. We'd talk them through how to interpret the report, how to use this information,

00:09:40.080 --> 00:09:44.719
how to think about their networks, and make strategies for how to leverage them. So it was

00:09:44.719 --> 00:09:49.919
all data driven, but we were running it more like a professional development workshop, focusing on

00:09:49.919 --> 00:09:56.000
helping everyone, rather than just running the survey that's just some task on a big list they

00:09:56.000 --> 00:10:02.719
needed to complete. In practice, for the implementation, the questionnaire itself,

00:10:02.719 --> 00:10:07.359
we were just running something using Qualtrics. We would then take the information from the

00:10:07.359 --> 00:10:13.599
Qualtrics API, put it into PDF reports in Markdown, and then distribute it to the employees via email.

00:10:13.599 --> 00:10:17.840
So very basic stuff, there's nothing technically really sophisticated here,

00:10:18.559 --> 00:10:22.159
but the big picture was thinking through what does this process look like.

00:10:23.359 --> 00:10:27.280
So in building this questionnaire, we were kind of walking people through this process of how do I

00:10:27.280 --> 00:10:32.320
map out my network. I'm picking a context in the workplace, I'm identifying key people,

00:10:32.479 --> 00:10:37.440
I'm describing network connections between them, and thinking about everyone and how everything's

00:10:37.440 --> 00:10:43.760
interrelated. And what we saw is that even with this very simple, very straightforward-seeming

00:10:43.760 --> 00:10:49.520
approach, we were able to get good results. We felt that we were able, participants said they

00:10:49.520 --> 00:10:55.679
were able to better make changes and better understand their network, and overall, without

00:10:55.679 --> 00:11:00.799
giving any information to the management or having to do like any direct exchange, we were able to

00:11:00.799 --> 00:11:06.400
get better quality data for our own research. So we were protecting participants' privacy, and we

00:11:06.400 --> 00:11:12.080
were doing interventions in the organization from this bottom-up perspective rather than a top-down

00:11:12.080 --> 00:11:18.880
one. So why did this work? And these are some of the most important points I want to make in my

00:11:18.880 --> 00:11:26.239
presentation today. The reason participants found value and the reason they provided good information

00:11:26.239 --> 00:11:30.640
is because we were meeting participants and trying to help them. They were filling out something

00:11:30.640 --> 00:11:35.440
that was for their own benefit and where we were engaging them with the results. So the incentives

00:11:35.440 --> 00:11:42.400
were right. When we sent out these reports, we were giving them tools to better understand the data.

00:11:43.520 --> 00:11:51.679
So our reports looked something like this. The very first version was just very simple PDFs,

00:11:51.679 --> 00:11:56.640
but we were helping people map out their networks. We were describing different properties of their

00:11:56.640 --> 00:12:02.000
networks and giving them their own score compared to other different groups in their organization

00:12:02.000 --> 00:12:07.119
and other groups in general, helping them understand what do I want my network to look like?

00:12:07.119 --> 00:12:13.919
How can I strategize about it? What do I want to change? And by taking this sort of expertise that

00:12:13.919 --> 00:12:20.239
we had and turning it into something accessible to the survey respondents, we were able to empower

00:12:20.239 --> 00:12:31.359
them to understand, reflect, and make changes. So a key part was we let participants reflect.

00:12:33.119 --> 00:12:38.320
A lot of people mentioned that they found value just in that first stage of this process where

00:12:38.320 --> 00:12:43.359
they were just filling out the questionnaire. And this was surprising to us, but after a while,

00:12:43.359 --> 00:12:48.640
it started to make sense. Everyone knows in their head that, like, oh, networking is important,

00:12:48.640 --> 00:12:53.200
building interpersonal connections, and having someone to go to for advice in the workplace is

00:12:53.200 --> 00:12:58.640
important, but people have busy calendars. You often don't set aside time in your day and say,

00:12:58.640 --> 00:13:03.440
I'm going to deliberately reflect on what's going on in my organization. I'm going to map everything

00:13:03.440 --> 00:13:08.799
out. I'm going to think of different strategies and what I should be doing differently. Maybe you

00:13:08.799 --> 00:13:14.799
do, but I think most of us do not, are not that deliberate in our planning. And having an exercise

00:13:14.880 --> 00:13:19.280
where participants had time to do this, had time to reflect and answer these questions for

00:13:19.280 --> 00:13:25.919
themselves was beneficial. And this was also beneficial in sort of launching organizational

00:13:25.919 --> 00:13:32.159
changes because participants could bring in their own context. Yes, we're getting quantitative data

00:13:32.159 --> 00:13:38.320
on the networks, but there's so much more going on in organizations that's not reflected in the data.

00:13:38.320 --> 00:13:42.239
The people that really know their jobs, that really understand what's going on, what needs

00:13:42.239 --> 00:13:47.919
to improve, how to make changes, are the people doing those jobs day in and day out. There's so

00:13:47.919 --> 00:13:53.840
much qualitative and subjective context they can bring in that positions them in a good place to

00:13:53.840 --> 00:13:59.280
make changes and to interpret the results. Rather than me having to understand all the minutia of

00:13:59.280 --> 00:14:02.719
their jobs, having to shadow them in order to understand what should they do differently,

00:14:02.719 --> 00:14:08.479
what's going on, if we give them access to the data, if we walk them through how to interpret

00:14:08.479 --> 00:14:12.719
network data, they can bring in their own context and hopefully better understand it.

00:14:13.760 --> 00:14:18.880
For instance, one of our participants described coming into a new company and when they were

00:14:18.880 --> 00:14:22.400
looking at their network, they were thinking about these different friend groups within the firm.

00:14:23.280 --> 00:14:28.320
They were thinking about their position and eventually they were able to make a strategy

00:14:28.320 --> 00:14:33.359
based off of their desire to connect to that sort of third friend group. But they're pulling in all

00:14:33.359 --> 00:14:39.760
the subjective knowledge that we as researchers don't necessarily have. And when we give data back

00:14:39.760 --> 00:14:46.479
to all the participants, it lets them make a lot of changes. So that's the big picture of how we saw

00:14:46.479 --> 00:14:53.520
value in kind of flipping the survey approach into something user-facing. So that was the first

00:14:53.520 --> 00:14:59.440
version of our solution. What we quickly realized was it wasn't very engaging and it wasn't very

00:14:59.520 --> 00:15:04.559
immediate. People wanted the ability to play around with the responses, see what's going on,

00:15:04.559 --> 00:15:10.080
and get immediate feedback. So that's where after building that Markdown version, we then later

00:15:10.080 --> 00:15:16.320
switched to a version using Shiny and Quarto to deliver something more interactive. So building a

00:15:16.320 --> 00:15:21.599
web app that's going to pull in both the question answering components and the immediately getting

00:15:21.599 --> 00:15:28.640
feedback as you go into one integrated experience. It no longer feels as much like a survey, but it's

00:15:28.640 --> 00:15:34.719
a good platform to see what do my networks look like, think about what can it change, how do I

00:15:34.719 --> 00:15:40.479
compare to others, and providing that information and context is very powerful. But definitely

00:15:40.479 --> 00:15:47.760
rethinking the platform and putting it into that format was very beneficial. So overall, what have

00:15:47.760 --> 00:15:54.479
I kind of talked about today? I've talked about rethinking the way we collect data when we have to

00:15:54.479 --> 00:15:59.919
ask a human for that data, thinking about empowering the respondents, and thinking about

00:15:59.919 --> 00:16:05.359
the way we make change in organizations. So rather than just thinking it's going to be a survey,

00:16:05.359 --> 00:16:09.280
I'm going to fill out a survey, and then someone's going to come up with the answer.

00:16:09.840 --> 00:16:14.640
Either I'm going to give a dashboard and management's going to come up with the answer,

00:16:14.640 --> 00:16:20.400
or I'm going to come up with the answer and pass it off to management. Instead, let's give the

00:16:20.400 --> 00:16:24.559
information to everyone and help everyone make changes based off of what we've learned.

00:16:25.280 --> 00:16:30.960
So blurring that divide between surveys, analysis, and interventions into one platform that's going

00:16:30.960 --> 00:16:38.000
to put them all together and help everyone be engaged in the process. So I hope that based off

00:16:38.000 --> 00:16:42.719
of this, if you're collecting data yourself, you can start to consider this role of power.

00:16:43.280 --> 00:16:48.559
Who has it? Who's going to make changes? And how can we make better experiences for the respondents?

00:16:49.359 --> 00:16:52.880
It's more than just asking people or forcing people to complete a survey.

00:16:54.000 --> 00:16:58.320
If we think through this approach, we can get better quality data, we can help people out,

00:16:59.200 --> 00:17:03.679
and we can create resources that we can use in lots of contexts. So after building this tool,

00:17:03.679 --> 00:17:07.839
we've used it for teaching exercises, we've used it for leadership development programs and

00:17:07.839 --> 00:17:12.160
organizations, we've used it as sort of interventions or organizational surveys.

00:17:12.719 --> 00:17:16.160
But building that kind of platform that helps everyone can be very valuable.

00:17:16.719 --> 00:17:22.160
If we kind of use interactive tools to move outside that traditional kind of data collection,

00:17:22.160 --> 00:17:30.000
data analysis paradigm. Thank you so much for listening today. If you're interested in hearing

00:17:30.000 --> 00:17:34.239
more about what I did, seeing some of the code, or if you're interested in using this type of tool

00:17:34.239 --> 00:17:39.680
in your own context, definitely reach out to me. I'll also be on the academic job market

00:17:39.680 --> 00:17:43.599
for positions starting in fall 2025. Thank you for listening today.

00:17:51.760 --> 00:17:57.680
Thank you. We have time for a couple of questions. It seems like you come to this work with a strong

00:17:57.680 --> 00:18:01.280
theoretical background. What did you find most surprising about your results?

00:18:02.239 --> 00:18:10.319
I think the most surprising thing for me is I thought the value that I thought the value for

00:18:10.319 --> 00:18:16.479
participants would be really hard to get out of it. Once we started delivering these reports to

00:18:16.479 --> 00:18:22.000
participants and asking them what was valuable, participants started saying, oh, it was valuable

00:18:22.000 --> 00:18:26.640
even before the report. Just even once we had the most basic version where we were doing a

00:18:26.640 --> 00:18:31.920
Qualtrics survey and that would be put into a report, just filling out the Qualtrics survey,

00:18:31.920 --> 00:18:36.479
some of them said they had value because they didn't do that reflection. And I realized there's

00:18:36.479 --> 00:18:42.560
so much space to not just think about these surveys as like, oh, I'm getting data, but as

00:18:42.560 --> 00:18:47.599
more of a guided experience, more of like just thinking through questions can be valuable.

00:18:47.599 --> 00:18:51.119
And it doesn't all have to be researcher-basing. Thank you.

00:18:52.000 --> 00:18:57.839
One last question. Your individual feedback reports were based on networks. Are there areas

00:18:57.839 --> 00:19:00.560
or types of information that are missed by this approach?

00:19:02.000 --> 00:19:07.439
Definitely, there's so much information. I think anytime you've put a survey together on anything,

00:19:07.439 --> 00:19:12.160
you're missing a ton of information. The best you can kind of maybe do is having like open-ended

00:19:12.160 --> 00:19:17.520
like text entry questions, but even that's limited. That's one of the big things I kind of

00:19:17.680 --> 00:19:21.520
the big things I kind of liked about this approach, thinking about it from an intervention

00:19:21.520 --> 00:19:27.359
angle, is yes, we're giving them network information and that's very limited. But once

00:19:27.359 --> 00:19:32.959
we ask people, what were your takeaways? What did you change? Like the example with the quote I gave,

00:19:32.959 --> 00:19:38.479
they were bringing in so much context that was outside of the network information. And both that

00:19:38.479 --> 00:19:42.400
and the network information together kind of informed their decisions and choices. There's

00:19:42.400 --> 00:19:49.119
so much richness in what they know. It's way, way more helpful to give the information to them

00:19:49.119 --> 00:19:53.680
in an accessible format than I think it would be for me to try and understand their jobs or figure

00:19:53.680 --> 00:20:00.239
out all that context. I just couldn't do it. So I think with the participants being empowered,

00:20:01.040 --> 00:20:04.319
they can understand that context and additional information so much better.

00:20:04.880 --> 00:20:05.520
Thank you.

00:20:05.520 --> 00:20:09.839
Let's thank Brennan again for his talk.

